message: I don't agree. There is no landscape to speak of in this picture.
The dual is used in Lithuanian; it is used in certain dialects, and, to a certain extent, also in the standard language. Therefore, it should be included here as well.

Considering Breton and Cornish are described as Southwestern Brittonic languages, Welsh should be described as a Western Brittonic language. There's no reason at all to leave this out in this case, when its sister languages are described the same way. To me, a reader, having it described as Western Brittonic is more meaningful.
It don't see any harm in it; especially since this episode was important, being the last one.

/* Hungarian being a part of the Ugric branch */ new section

Firstly: you're wrong. That the Hungarian language belongs to the Ugric branch has been part of the consensus for many years (and for at least ten in this article). Secondly: that's not how Wikipedia works. A user, irrespective of his knowledge in the linguistic field, can't put any controversial fact into an article without providing a source and tell other users that they should discuss the matter somewhere else. Until then a source has been provided, Hungarian is part of the Ugric branch.

Hungarian is considered a part of the Ugric branch. As far as I can see, there are no doubts about this in linguistic circles; at least not in well-respected ones. Since this information has been part of the article for years, I say that the person who has reason to doubt should provide sources and not the other way around. I'm reverting.
